<subSubSection id="69AE97B7E456FFDDFF07357E5F4EF968" pageId="12" pageNumber="463" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="210BC43CE456FFDDFF07357E5F4EF968" blockId="12.[151,1437,150,1689]" pageId="12" pageNumber="463">
<emphasis id="13C0182EE456FFDDFF07357E5F04F984" bold="true" box="[199,334,1627,1653]" pageId="12" pageNumber="463">Etymology.</emphasis>
This specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis id="13C0182EE456FFDDFCA0357E5DCEF985" box="[864,900,1627,1652]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="463">tri-</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="13C0182EE456FFDDFC7B357E5A45F985" box="[955,1039,1627,1652]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="463">striatus</emphasis>
, referring to the three stripes in the forewing.
</paragraph>
